    {
      "title": "Independent pronouns (ni, kai, ke…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say who you mean",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "The free pronouns are ni (I), kai (you, m), ke (you, f), shi (he), ita (she), mu (we), ku (you all), su (they). Hausa marks gender in the second and third person singular — kai to a man, ke to a woman.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} malami ne.",
          "answer": "Ni",
          "translation": "I am a teacher.",
          "hint": "the 'I' pronoun",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} tana nan.",
          "answer": "Ita",
          "translation": "She is here.",
          "hint": "the 'she' pronoun",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ɗalibi ne.",
          "answer": "Shi",
          "translation": "He is a student.",
          "hint": "he",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} muna nan.",
          "answer": "Mu",
          "translation": "We are here.",
          "hint": "we — emphatic",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} malama ce.",
          "answer": "Ita",
          "translation": "She is a teacher.",
          "hint": "she",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} kana aiki.",
          "answer": "Kai",
          "translation": "You (masculine) are working.",
          "hint": "you (m) — emphatic",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Identity with ne / ce",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what someone or something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Identity sentences end in ne (masculine/plural) or ce (feminine): Ni malami ne (I am a teacher), Ita malama ce (She is a teacher), Su ɗalibai ne (They are students). The particle agrees with the SUBJECT noun's gender.",
      "culture_note": "Hausa has two genders, masculine and feminine — most feminines end in -a, and ne/ce is your first meeting with that system.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ni malami {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ne",
          "translation": "I am a (male) teacher.",
          "hint": "which particle? check gender/number of the noun",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ita malama {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ce",
          "translation": "She is a (female) teacher.",
          "hint": "which particle? mota is feminine",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Su ɗalibai {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ne",
          "translation": "They are students.",
          "hint": "which particle? check gender/number of the noun",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Wannan mota {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ce",
          "translation": "This is a car.",
          "hint": "which particle? mota is feminine",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Audu manomi {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ne",
          "translation": "Audu is a farmer.",
          "hint": "which particle? check gender/number of the noun",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Wannan ruwa {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ne",
          "translation": "This is water.",
          "hint": "which particle? check gender/number of the noun",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Completive aspect (na, ka, ya, ta…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what happened (done and finished)",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Hausa conjugates with aspect pronouns before the verb. Completive (did/has done): na (I), ka/kin (you m/f), ya (he), ta (she), mun (we), kun (you all), sun (they): Na ci abinci (I ate food), Sun tafi (They left).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ci abinci.",
          "answer": "Na",
          "translation": "I ate food.",
          "hint": "completive 'I'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} tafi kasuwa.",
          "answer": "Ta",
          "translation": "She went to the market.",
          "hint": "completive 'she'",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} zo gida.",
          "answer": "Sun",
          "translation": "They came home.",
          "hint": "they — completive",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} sayi shinkafa.",
          "answer": "Mun",
          "translation": "We bought rice.",
          "hint": "we — completive",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} karanta littafi.",
          "answer": "Ya",
          "translation": "He read a book.",
          "hint": "he — completive",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} dafa abinci.",
          "answer": "Kin",
          "translation": "You (feminine) cooked food.",
          "hint": "you (f) — completive",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Continuous aspect (ina, kana, yana…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what is happening",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 4,
      "explanation": "The continuous uses -na pronouns plus the verbal noun: Ina cin abinci (I am eating), Yana aiki (He is working), Muna zuwa (We are coming). Ina also opens 'where' questions: Ina kake? (Where are you?).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
