    {
      "title": "Existence: akwai / babu",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what there is and isn't",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 6,
      "explanation": "Akwai asserts existence, babu denies it: Akwai ruwa (There is water), Babu kuɗi (There is no money). With 'have' meaning: Akwai littafi a wurina (I have a book — lit. there's a book at my place); everyday 'have' also uses da: Ina da mota (I have a car).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ruwa a gida.",
          "answer": "Akwai",
          "translation": "There is water at home.",
          "hint": "'there is'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} kuɗi.",
          "answer": "Babu",
          "translation": "There is no money.",
          "hint": "'there is not'",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} mutane da yawa a kasuwa.",
          "answer": "Akwai",
          "translation": "There are many people at the market.",
          "hint": "existence",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} abinci a gida.",
          "answer": "Babu",
          "translation": "There is no food at home.",
          "hint": "absence",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ruwa a rijiya?",
          "answer": "Akwai",
          "translation": "Is there water in the well?",
          "hint": "existence, question",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} wata matsala.",
          "answer": "Babu",
          "translation": "There is no problem.",
          "hint": "absence",
          "display_order": 6
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Negation ba … ba",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Deny statements",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Most negation wraps the clause in ba … ba: Ban ci ba (I didn't eat — ba+na fuses to ban), Ba ta zo ba (She didn't come). The continuous negates with bā (single): Ba na zuwa (I am not coming/going).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ci abinci ba.",
          "answer": "Ban",
          "translation": "I did not eat food.",
          "hint": "negative + 'I' fused — the opening half",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ba ta zo {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ba",
          "translation": "She did not come.",
          "hint": "the closing half of the frame",
          "display_order": 2
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} zo ba.",
          "answer": "Bai",
          "translation": "He didn't come.",
          "hint": "he + negative completive",
          "display_order": 3
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ba su zo {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ba",
          "translation": "They didn't come.",
          "hint": "the closing half of the frame",
          "display_order": 4
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ta dafa abinci ba.",
          "answer": "Ba",
          "translation": "She didn't cook food.",
          "hint": "the opening half of the frame",
          "display_order": 5
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ba mu gan shi {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ba",
          "translation": "We didn't see him.",
          "hint": "the closing half of the frame",
